The Big Three all launched their new 1949 models at once, the first postwar designs. Ford's '49 models, the result of wartime design work, were an upgrade in every way except the drivetrain which for the time being was still the same old roster of flathead V8s plus the I6. Ford's slab styling was roughly midway between GM's sleek aircraft designs and Chrysler's staid boxes, and it was the most favored of the three by European automobile designers. The antiquated solid axle and leaf spring suspension was replaced by a modern independent suspension with front coil springs and rear leaf springs. The equally ancient torque tube driveshaft was replaced by a Hotchkiss unit.

Helped by an extended model year, Ford moved 1.1 million cars. The '49 Fords had been rushed into production and numerous quality defects soon became apparent, so efforts were made to correct them on the '50 models. Issues with the front end components were corrected and more insulation to reduce interior noise. The door locks were also improved after numerous issues with them coming open easily on the road. Sales increased to 1.2 million for the model year. Ford had not been able to bring out a true hardtop coupe in time to match Chevrolet so they made do with the Crestliner, a pseudo-hardtop with a padded vinyl roof. The soon-to-be-familiar Country Squire nameplate appeared on station wagon models.

The 1951 model year was the last of this generation of Fords. The company's first automatic transmission, the three speed Ford-O-Matic, made its debut and a key ignition mechanism replaced the push button start. With the onset of the Korean War, sales dipped slightly to just under 1.1 million.
